# Hardware Reference

Use `/home/pi/rythm-jump` as the canonical reference for Raspberry Pi hardware communication. Adapt pin counts and patterns to Toxic Game's single-strip, two-end layout.

## Prototype Defaults (`rythm_jump.toml`)

```toml
[gpio]
left_contact_pin = 17
right_contact_pin = 27

[led]
count = 60
pin = 18
freq_hz = 800000
dma = 10
invert = false
brightness = 255
channel = 0
```

## Wiring (from prototype README)

- **LED strip:** WS2811, 5V/12V/24V; data via level shifter (74AHCT125), ~220–249Ω series resistor, 1000µF cap on power
- **Buttons:** Momentary contact switches with 10kΩ pull-up; read as active-low on GPIO
- **Power:** Buck converter from 24V rail; watch for undervoltage on Pi

## Prototype Code to Reuse / Study

| Concern | Path |
|---------|------|
| GPIO input | `rythm_jump/hw/gpio_input.py` |
| LED output | `rythm_jump/hw/led_output.py` |
| LED frame building | `rythm_jump/engine/led_frames.py` |
| Hardware config | `rythm_jump/config.py` |
| Debug CLI | `rythm_jump/cli.py` (`rj-debug gpio`, `rj-debug led`) |

## Toxic Game Differences from Prototype

- Prototype splits strip into **left/right halves** for two lanes; Toxic Game uses **ends of one strip** for two players with traveling lights
- Prototype uses JSON charts; Toxic Game uses **plain-text tap note files** + separate song config
- Prototype has a web UI; Toxic Game is **headless** (admin tools are CLI or separate scripts)

## Dev Without Hardware

- GPIO: return `False` when `RPi.GPIO` unavailable (prototype pattern)
- LED: `NoOpLedOutput` / `SimLedOutput` for tests (prototype pattern)
